snippet.textDisplay:
If you want to know what happend next.

"Cadbury was in the den asking the Dragons for £75k for a 5% share of the business. The money was to be invested in two key areas of the business: developing new products including those using online personalisation, and expanding the Love Cocoa team.
The deal with Tej Lalvani saw Cadbury revert to the infamous wall twice to think about his options before finally accepting £75k for a 15% share. However, following a series of lengthy discussions and having met Lalvani several times after the episode was filmed, Cadbury has since decided to go it alone."

snippet.textDisplay: Lets explore the hypocritical, double standards and slimy sycophantism that curtains their insatiable greed. Check out the eyebrows of greed twitching as it dawns this guy is a Cadbury - what an opportunity for the dragons to get their fingers sticky from not sharing... they look past the stuttering, the lousy pitch, the really bad business practices because of name. Hope it bites them in the rear end, lol, myopic money grabbing brown-nosers.

snippet.textDisplay: When Deborah mentioned her distaste at the branding, I thought James should have used his name but he did it, (in my opinion) absolutely correctly .. by James Cadbury.  I fail to see how Mondelez (the owner of the Cadbury brand) could possibly sue someone for using his own name.  None of the colours or fonts in any way even hint at the Cadbury brand, indeed in his position, I would add a little story to the rear packaging about how his great great grandfather started the company mentioning that it is today owned by Mondelez.  I agree with Peter that they should have a go at him as this would give a huge amount of free publicity, possibly without the possibility of Mondelez seeing a return on their legal 'investment'.  I very much doubt that this multinational would take this action knowing what the effect would be on their market share and that the popular press would be overjoyed to take up James's cause.

snippet.textDisplay: I wish great success and longevity to Mr James Cadbury and I hope that someday, somehow his company manages to incorporate the "Cadbury" brand back into it's "rightful home". I worked for this great company in Port Elizabeth, South Africa, for many years (am now retired) and I can truly say that it was the best work experience and company that I've ever worked at. It was a privelege to work for Cadbury and I owe all of my growth, educational progression, and career success to them. Best wishes to you Mr James Cadbury!!!! I hope to see your products in South Africa in the future.
